# Peekie

`peekie` is a CLI for Xcode `.xcresult` bundles. Use it before composing `xcrun xcresulttool` calls by hand.

## Subcommands

```
peekie tests     <xcresult>  [--format json|list|sonar]  default: list
peekie warnings  <xcresult>  [--format json|list]        default: json
peekie errors    <xcresult>  [--format json|list]        default: json
peekie coverage  <xcresult>  [--format json|list]        default: json
```

Each subcommand runs only the `xcresulttool` / `xccov` calls it needs.

## When to use which

- "What tests failed?" → `peekie tests <x> --include failure,mixed`
- "What warnings?" → `peekie warnings <x>`
- "Why is the build broken?" → `peekie errors <x>`
- "What's the coverage?" → `peekie coverage <x>`
- "SonarQube report" → `peekie tests <x> --format sonar --tests-path <dir>`

## Output

- `peekie warnings` / `peekie errors` emit a flat JSON array of `{file, line, column, type, message}`. Use `jq` to filter.
- `peekie coverage` emits `{coverage, modules: [{name, coverage, files: […]}]}`.
- `peekie tests --format json` emits the full Report shape (modules → suites → tests). Coverage / files arrays are empty because the subcommand doesn't fetch them.

## Recipes

```bash
# Build-failed gate
errors=$(peekie errors Build.xcresult | jq 'length')
[ "$errors" -gt 0 ] && exit 1

# Coverage as a number
peekie coverage Tests.xcresult | jq '.coverage'

# Warnings grouped by type
peekie warnings Build.xcresult | jq 'group_by(.type) | map({type: .[0].type, count: length})'
```

## Filtering

- `peekie tests` has `--include success,failure,…` for statuses.
- `peekie warnings` / `peekie errors` have **no `--include` flag** — filter with `jq` instead.

## Install

If `peekie` is missing: `mise use github:dodobrands/peekie`, or download from [Releases](https://github.com/dodobrands/Peekie/releases). Don't fall back to `swift run peekie …`.

## Don't

- Don't invent `--include-coverage` / `--include-warnings` / `--include-tests` flags on the CLI — the subcommand determines what gets fetched.
- Don't expect `peekie tests` to print coverage or `peekie coverage` to print suites. Compose two calls if you need both.
